Here's a minimal example:

**Product.cs**
```csharp
public class Product
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
}
```

**ViewModel.cs**
```csharp
using System.Collections.ObjectModel;

public class ProductViewModel
{
    public ObservableCollection<Product> Products { get; } = new()
    {
        new Product { Name = "Widget", Price = 9.99m },
        new Product { Name = "Gadget", Price = 24.95m }
    };
}
```

**MainPage.xaml**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             xmlns:local="clr-namespace:YourNamespace"
             x:Class="YourNamespace.MainPage"
             x:DataType="local:ProductViewModel">

    <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Products}"
                    ItemsLayout="VerticalList">
        <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
            <DataTemplate x:DataType="local:Product">
                <HorizontalStackLayout Padding="10" Spacing="10">
                    <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="18" />
                    <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='{0:C}'}"
                           FontSize="18" TextColor="Green" />
                </HorizontalStackLayout>
            </DataTemplate>
        </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
    </CollectionView>
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**
- **`x:DataType`** on the page targets the VM; on the `DataTemplate` it targets `Product` — this enables **compiled bindings** (build-time checked, faster).
- `CollectionView` scrolls vertically by default (`VerticalList`).
- `StringFormat='{0:C}'` formats the price as currency.

Set the `BindingContext` in code-behind:

```csharp
public MainPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = new ProductViewModel();
}
```
